<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Belgian rates cut in wake of austerity plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BELGIAN government agreed early yesterday to a wide-ranging austerity
plan, prompting a reduction in two leading interest rates and a euphoric
reaction in Belgian financial markets.
After 16 hours of talks, ministers backed a three-point package which
imposes curbs on social spending and limits wage increases to the rate of
inflation until the end of 1996.
The pact also contains new measures to tackle rising unemployment,
particularly among young people.
The Belgian National Bank responded by cutting the discount rate from 6 per
cent to 5.5 per cent, while reducing the money market rate from 9.4 per cent
to 8.3 per cent. The Belgian franc strengthened against the D-Mark to close
at BFr21.25 yesterday on hopes the rate cut would help revive the economy.
Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene, prime minister, hailed the agreement as good for
Belgium and good for Europe.
The plan draws some inspiration from the forthcoming European Commission
White Paper on competitiveness, growth and employment which will be the
centrepiece of next month's EU summit in Brussels, to be chaired by the
Belgian presidency.
Among the social pact's chief points are a planned reduction of around
BFr75bn (Pounds 1.4bn) in spending on health care, family allowances and
pensions.
The most sensitive proposal is to reduce family allowances in relation to
family income, starting at a threshold of BF750,000 a year.
In order to promote job creation, the government proposes to reduce sharply
the costs of hiring labour.
Businesses will be fully exempt from paying social costs in the first year
when employing people under 26 years old, sliding down to 75 per cent and 50
per cent exemptions in the second and third years.
It also proposes job-sharing to expand the number of people in work.
To raise revenue, the government proposes to raise withholding tax on
interest income from 10.3 per cent to 13.39 per cent.
The witholding tax on dividends is planned to fall from 25 per cent to 13.4
per cent.
The fate of the package will depend partly on whether Mr Dehaene's fragile
centre-left coalition can win support among opposition parties and blunt
opposition within Belgium's public sector trades unions.
This week, rolling strikes took place in Belgium in protest against the
pact.
Initial reaction among potential opponents was guarded. The Socialist party
declared that it had helped to make the austerity plan more equitable, but
it would remain vigilant on the application of the planned measures.
The Belgian economy is expected to shrink by 1.5 percent this year. It has
the highest public debt in the EU as a proportion of GDP.
Worries about this indebtedness have unnerved financial markets, and damaged
confidence in Belgium's claims to be part of a hard-core currency club built
around the D-Mark, particularly after the collapse of the exchange rate
mechanism on so-called Black Wednesday, September 16, last year.
On the markets yesterday, Belgian government bonds climbed nearly a point
following the cut in interest rates.
The Bel-20 index of leading shares jumped 21.8 to close at 1,397, despite
earlier worries that the effect of new taxes might undermine the positive
impact of lower interest rates.
Currencies
International Capital Markets
World Stocks - Second Section
</TEXT>
