<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / S Africa's blacks get the vote: Deal on majority rule
constitution ends 350 years of white oppression
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICA last night adopted a majority rule constitution, effectively
bringing to an end 350 years of white minority oppression and giving blacks
the vote for the first time.
'We have reached the end of an era . . . millions who were not allowed to
vote, will do so. I, too, for the first time in my short life, will vote,'
said Mr Nelson Mandela, the African National Congress leader and the man
widely expected to become the country's next president.
Mr FW de Klerk, the South African president and the man whose vision and
reforms made the new constitution possible, will remain in charge until next
April's general election when the new constitution will take effect.
He heralded the document as the 'distillation of the dreams of generations
of disenfranchised South Africans'.
Weary negotiators reached agreement on the historic 158-page document late
last night after years of negotiation. The process was set in train when
government ministers met Mr Nelson Mandela in the months preceding his
release from jail in 1990, after 27 years in detention for opposing the
racist state.
The constitution will remain in force for up to five years and is based on
traditional western values which contrast sharply with apartheid, one of the
most repressive regimes in history.
It guarantees multi-party democracy, equality before the law, fundamental
human rights and freedoms, an independent judiciary and a free press.
Mr Matthew Phosa, the ANC's constitutional negotiator, said the 21 parties
which agreed the constitution had dug 'the grave for apartheid'.
Mr Roelf Meyer, the government's chief negotiator, shocked delegates to the
negotiating council when he announced that the government had agreed to a
very weak form of multiracial power-sharing, a capitulation by the ruling
National party.
All parties with more than 5 per cent of the vote will be granted a seat in
cabinet in a government of national unity, with two deputy presidents to be
chosen from the two top parties. The president will be elected by the
national assembly.
But the new constitution has powerful opponents, among them the mainly Zulu
Inkatha Freedom party of Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi and the white right
wing, led by retired army general Constand Viljoen.
They form the so-called 'Freedom Alliance' which poses a substantial threat
to the stability of the government which will emerge after elections on
April 27 next year.
Mr de Klerk has left open the possibility that the Alliance may ratify the
constitution after it has been adopted by the other 21 parties, but this
seemed increasingly unlikely.
Concessions were made to the Alliance in last night's debate, including
allowing regions to write their own constitutions and requiring a two-thirds
majority of the regional house of assembly, the senate, to change the powers
of regions. But these did not appear sufficient to bring the Alliance back
on board.
With a low-level civil war already raging in Natal province between Inkatha
and the ANC, and with the right wing heavily armed and well trained, the two
could prevent elections altogether unless they are accommodated. The
president will try for a consensus, but will have the final say where this
is not possible.
De Klerk climbdown seals deal on constitution, Page 6
Constitution details, Page 6
Editorial Comment, Page 21
S Africa survey, Pages 35-40
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZAZ  South Africa, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
