<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Nigeria's civilian leader ousted by military
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS and MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA'S political crisis deepened last night as General Sani Abacha, the
defence minister, deposed the country's civilian head of state.
Chief Ernest Shonekan, leader of the interim administration appointed in
August, was said by aides to have been forced to resign by senior army
officers at a four-hour meeting in the capital, Abuja, yesterday.
Gen Abacha, a key member of former military governments, has been the most
powerful figure in the interim civilian-led administration since it was
appointed by the former military president, General Ibrahim Babangida. The
army remained in charge, however.
Mr Shonekan, a lawyer and industrialist, said in a statement read by an
announcer on state television he had resigned after consultations with
military chiefs, including Gen Abacha.
The statement said: 'They expressed serious concern about the general
uneasiness in the country and apparent lack of stability over the past few
months.
'They spoke about restiveness of the rank and file in the military.'
Last night the British government condemned the move. A foreign office
statement said: 'The foreign secretary (Mr Douglas Hurd) deplores the
decision of the Nigerian military to reverse the democratic process in
Nigeria and to dissolve all democratically elected institutions.'
'Military dictatorship cannot solve Nigeria's problems. This is a serious
step backwards not merely for Nigeria but for Africa as a whole,' the
statement added.
Tension has been rising since last week's decision to increase domestic fuel
prices six fold, which triggered demonstrations in Lagos and a general
strike, which entered its third day yesterday.
The development, which Mr Shonekan's supporters described as 'an effective
coup' will be a major setback to hopes for the country's economic recovery,
and raises fears of instability should Gen Abacha not have the full backing
of the armed forces.
But these fears were downplayed last night by sources close to the military
establishment. Mr Shonekan, a respected businessman who was first appointed
chairman of a civilian administration in December 1992, is a technocrat who
made economic recovery his priority.
Working closely with the private sector, he drew up a policy blueprint
designed to win the backing of the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund and pave the way to rescheduling of the country Dollars 30bn (Pounds
20.1bn) external debt.
Removing the fuel subsidy, which made Nigerian petrol among the cheapest in
the world, was a fundamental part of the programme.
The country has been losing revenue with fuel intended for the domestic
market being smuggled - often with the connivance of senior military
officers - into neighbouring states, where fuel prices are several times
higher.
Successive efforts to raise the price met fierce resistance from Nigerian
consumers, convinced that the additional revenue would go not into
government services but disappear in the corruption endemic in Nigeria.
The change of power means plans to hold a fresh election next February may
also have to be suspended.
</TEXT>
