<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 93 / Fall in RPI boosts hopes of lower rates: Retail sales growth
remains disappointing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP DROP in inflation last month, together with disappointing growth in
shop sales, yesterday revived hopes that Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor,
will cut interest rates around Budget day.
Intense price competition, particularly among food retailers, pulled the
retail prices index down by 0.1 per cent in October, cutting the annual rate
of inflation to 1.4 per cent last month from 1.8 per cent in September.
As a further sign of falling inflationary pressure in the UK, BP yesterday
announced it was cutting petrol prices by 9p a gallon, 2p a litre.
Underlying inflation - the RPI excluding mortgage interest payments - also
dropped 0.1 per cent on the month, returning the year-on-year rate of
underlying inflation to a 25-year low, reached in May, of 2.8 per cent. This
compares with 3.3 per cent in the year to September and the government's
target ceiling of 4 per cent. The fall in the headline rate means that
inflation has now been below 2 per cent for 10 consecutive months, the
longest run below this level since 1960.
The sluggish picture on prices coincided with and reflected other official
figures that showed retail sales growth slowing in October. Together the
figures underlined the patchiness of the recovery and consumers' reluctance
to spend.
Last month retail sales volumes rose a seasonally adjusted 0.1 per cent
compared with the previous month to stand 3.2 per cent higher than a year
ago. This was the lowest year-on-year rate of growth for five months.
Share prices rose on heightened expectations that bank base rates may be cut
from the 6 per cent level set in January. The FT-SE 100 share index closed
up 22.5 at 3,120. Gilts prices rose about a point in response to the low
inflation figures. But interest rate speculation hit sterling, which closed
in London down a pfennig at DM2.5175 and fell almost a cent to Dollars
1.477, before regaining some ground in New York.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial secretary to the Treasury, said the
figures showed the UK had a 'once in a generation' opportunity to break out
of inflationary cycles. 'I really do think it is time we broke out of the
British belief that unless we have got inflation we haven't got a buoyant
economy,' he said.
But the weakness of shop sales is likely to increase pressure on Mr Clarke
to minimise further tax rises in the November 30 Budget for fear of damaging
demand.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said the inflation and retail sales
figures illustrated the weakness of the recovery and called for interest
rates to be cut now in the interest of the economy and not when it was
politically right for the chancellor.
The latest drop in inflation reduces the chance that underlying inflation
will breach the government's 4 per cent target ceiling over the next few
months. The outlook, according to the Central Statistical Office, is that
inflation will remain subdued as big retailers compete to slash prices.
The most buoyant area of retail sales was household goods, 2.3 per cent
higher in the latest three months, compared with the previous three-month
period. Compared with a year ago, they were 10.1 per cent higher.
Seasonally adjusted retail sales values rose by 0.1 per cent on the month,
and their year-on-year rate slowed to 5.4 per cent in October from 6.1 per
cent in September.
