<PROFILE>_AN-DKQCRAG9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931117
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow at record high on hopes
for Nafta vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER A lacklustre start, blue chip stocks roared into record territory
yesterday as expectations that Congress would approve Nafta in today's
crucial vote helped the Dow Jones Industrial Average close above 3,700 for
the first time, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Industrial Average was 33.25 stronger at 3,710.77 and
the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 up 2.99 at 466.74. Secondary
indices, however, fared less well, with the American SE composite index
finishing down 3.09 at 474.73 and the Nasdaq composite 0.76 lower at 771.69.
New York SE volume came to 304m shares.
Trading was initially hampered by uncertainty surrounding the outcome of the
House of Representatives' vote (due some time tonight) on the North American
Free Trade Agreement.
The markets view passage of Nafta as bullish for equities - free trade
should promote exports and economic growth, say economists - but remain
concerned that a majority of House members may vote against the treaty on
the grounds that it will lead to a loss of US jobs to Mexico.
Both sides claimed yesterday that they had enough votes for victory, but
reports late in the day that President Clinton had locked up enough votes to
ensure Nafta passes into law provided stocks with a strong lift in the final
hour of trading.
The gains were achieved in spite of further declines in bond prices, which
pushed the yield on the benchmark 30-year bond up to 6.16 per cent and
fuelled fears that long-term interest rates may be on the rise.
Telefonos de Mexico, the market's biggest 'Nafta play', continued to be
buffeted by the uncertainty surrounding the treaty's fortunes. After posting
declines in the previous two trading days, Telmex yesterday rebounded
Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 56 7/8 in volume of 8m shares.
Among leading Dow stocks, General Electric climbed Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars
96 3/8 , IBM added Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 52 3/4 and General Motors rose
Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 52 3/4 . General Motors class 'E' shares, however,
fell Dollars 2 to Dollars 29 as investors reacted to news that the company
is considering using 185m of the shares to fund its pension liability if it
receives the go-ahead of regulators.
Much of the early weakness in the Dow was attributable to a sharp decline in
Caterpillar shares, which lost Dollars 3 to Dollars 86 7/8 before rallying
to end a net Dollars 1 1/8 down at Dollars 88 3/4 . The damage was inflicted
by a downgrade and lowered earnings forecast by broking house Donaldson
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
Canada
THE Toronto market retreated to a sharply lower close as today's US vote on
Nafta and tumbling natural resource shares weighed on confidence.
The TSE 300 composite index dropped 24.6 to 4,257.2, while trading volume
totalled 83.2m shares valued at CDollars 777m.
