<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / International Company News: QVC seeks Paramount bid 'poison
pill' ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
QVC Network, the US home shopping company, yesterday asked a US court to
throw out 'poison pill' provisions standing in the way of its hostile
Dollars 90 a share bid for Paramount Communications, the film studio and
book publishing group.
The company told the Delaware Chancery Court it wanted 'a level playing
field' that would enable it to fight fairly with Viacom, the cable
television company that has made an agreed bid for Paramount worth Dollars
85 a share.
Under the terms of the agreed bid, Viacom would get a Dollars 100m
consolation prize if a rival bidder won the battle, together with the right
to buy 20 per cent of Paramount's stock on favourable terms.
QVC claims the provisions are illegally hindering other bids. It told the
court yesterday: 'It is a breach of fiduciary duty for Paramount directors
to pull this poison pill for an inferior offer by Viacom.'
Paramount vigorously denied the claim and the outcome of the court case is
likely to prove decisive in the battle.
A fall in Paramount's share price in the last two days suggests that Wall
Street is putting its money on a victory for Viacom, the lower bidder.
Meanwhile, QVC reported third-quarter net income of Dollars 21.5m, an
increase of 31.5 per cent over the previous year's figure. Net income per
share rose only slightly from 40 cents to 42 cents because of an enlarged
equity base.
Nynex, the US regional telephone company that has formed an alliance with
Viacom in its bid for Paramount, yesterday challenged US laws preventing
telephone companies offering cable services in their own regions.
It filed a suit in the District Court in Portland, Maine, claiming the
restriction violated its constitutional right to free speech and deprived
customers of a full range of choices in the video services market.
</TEXT>
