<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / International Company News: Morgan Stanley up 64% in quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MORGAN Stanley, the US securities house, yesterday announced third quarter
earnings of Dollars 181.7m, up 64 per cent from a year earlier and in line
with analysts' expectations.
The results, however, were not as strong as in the record-breaking second
quarter, primarily because of lower trading and investment banking revenues.
Although the firm's overall earnings remained strong compared to previous
years, the quarter-on-quarter decline in revenues from Morgan Stanley's two
main businesses suggests that the unprecedented two-and-a-half year boom in
Wall Street profits may have passed its peak.
The firm said the drop in trading revenues was mostly the result of
unfavourable conditions in the mortgage-backed securities (MBS) market.
Trading revenues totalled Dollars 285.3m in the period, down from Dollars
300.8m a year ago and well below the record Dollars 517.9bn reported in the
second quarter.
Although Morgan Stanley did not provide details on the MBS situation,
several big Wall Street firms and institutional investors have encountered
problems in the MBS market recently.
This follows a surge in the number of borrowers paying off their mortgages
early, which has led to losses on portfolios of securities that pay only the
interest portion of a mortgage.
With trading revenues declining, investment banking took over as the firm's
main source of earnings during the quarter, bringing in a total of Dollars
295.5m, up 62 per cent from a year earlier.
The improvement was accredited to growth in structured debt underwriting
volumes, a strong equity new issues calendar, and an increase in mergers and
acquisitions and other corporate advisory business.
Brokerage commissions totalled in Dollars 101m in the quarter, up from
Dollars 76.3m a year earlier, and asset management and administration fees
contributed Dollars 67m, up from Dollars 51m. Interest and dividend income
climbed 61 per cent to Dollars 1.57bn.
Non-interest expenses increased 32 per cent to Dollars 757.6m, mostly
because of a rise in compensation payments that was related to the growth in
profits.
Morgan Stanley's shares closed up Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 76 1/4 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
