FT  17 NOV 93 / International Company News: JC Penney sets record as Dayton
Hudson slips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JC PENNEY, the fourth-largest US retailer, maintained its strong sales and
earnings momentum in the third quarter, while Dayton Hudson continued to
suffer from its heavy exposure to the sluggish Californian economy.
Penney, with nearly 1,300 department stores in 50 states and an extensive
catalogue-sales business, yesterday said net income, before an extraordinary
item, set a quarterly record at Dollars 221m, or 83 cents a share. The
result compares with Dollars 186m, or 70 cents, in the corresponding period
of 1992.
In the three months to the end of October, the company took a one-time
charge of Dollars 36m, or 14 cents, to cover early retirement of debt, plus
a Dollars 14m provision to adjust deferred taxes.
With both items included, net income was Dollars 185m, or 69 cents.
The improvement in earnings was struck on a 9.1 per cent advance in sales to
Dollars 4.76bn.
