<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Sheffield Insulations gives court
undertakings
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sheffield Insulations Group's subsidiary, Sheffield Insulations, has given
undertakings in the restrictive practices court not to give effect to
certain agreements which related to the supply of insulation products in
1986.
These agreements were alleged by the Office of Fair Trading to have been in
existence for only a fairly short time at the end of that year and were said
to have attempted to fix maximum discounts for the supply of certain
insulation materials.
Sheffield Insulations consistently denied that it had been party to such
agreement, but accepted that there had been an agreement to continue the
long-standing and accepted practice of quoting prices on the basis of
variable discounts from list prices.
The company said this was not effective to limit in any way the prices paid
by the customer and it was on this basis that it gave undertakings to the
court.
</TEXT>
