<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / UK Company News: Bryanston creditors can expect 40p in the
Pounds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CREDITORS to Bryanston, the insurance company in provisional liquidation,
can expect to receive to receive up to 40p in the pound, according to
proposals circulated yesterday.
Accounts for the year to December 31 1992 show that there are assets of
Pounds 86m against liabilities estimated at Pounds 216m. The provisional
liquidators at accountants Price Waterhouse suggest this will lead to a pay
out of 30p to 40p.
The details appear in documents distributed to creditors as part of a
proposed scheme of arrangement under English insolvency law.
Bryanston, and its sister company Trinity, entered provisional liquidation
in March last year. A scheme of arrangement for Trinity was proposed earlier
this year.
Actuarial estimates put gross reserves - allowing for substantial future
liabilities including legal claims in the US courts on pollution and
asbestosis - at Pounds 194m.
The document has been circulated to nearly 10,000 creditors identified by
the liquidators. They will vote on the proposals in January.
</TEXT>
