<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / BAA rises thanks to retailing strength
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RETAILING has become the largest single source of income for BAA, the
privatised British Airports Authority, which yesterday reported an 8.7 per
cent rise in first-half pre-tax profits to Pounds 237m, from Pounds 218m.
Apart from a 10 per cent increase in retail income, the higher earnings
reflected healthy growth in air travel, especially in the UK, and the
company's continuing drive to control costs.
Sir John Egan, chief executive, said the company was seeking to expand its
international airport activities in the US, Europe and Asia through
consultancy contracts, joint ventures and equity stakes. With a 70 per cent
share of the UK airport business already, BAA was not interested in
investing in new British ventures following the government's proposals to
privatise local authority airports.
Sir John confirmed that BAA was interested in proposals to privatise Rome's
Fumicino airport, adding that the company had been approached by numerous
authorities involving 20-30 airports to discuss co-operation and partnership
ventures. 'Many foreign governments are interested in bringing private
capital in their airports systems and they are looking at our successful
example,' he said.
He has been the architect of BAA's drive into retailing which accounted for
Pounds 250m of the company's total first-half revenues of Pounds 627m, up
16.5 per cent.
The contribution from retailing was higher than the Pounds 244m income
earned from aircraft landing charges. In spite of a 4.6 per cent increase in
passenger numbers, income from aircraft landing charges fell 0.7 per cent
because of the current regulatory pricing formula.
Sir John said BAA had added nearly 50 new airport shops in the past six
months bringing the total at its UK airports to just over 400.
BAA's latest traffic forecasts for its seven UK airports saw growth at a
rate of 3.8 per cent a year to the end of the century. The seven were
expected to handle 86m passengers by 1995 and 104m passengers by 2000
compared with 77m last year.
The interim dividend goes up 8 per cent to 6.75p. Earnings per share were
5.9 per cent higher at 34.2p, reflecting a higher tax charge.
Lex, Page 26
Market, Page 58
</TEXT>
