<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Hosokawa victory on reforms: Japanese vote for political
change ends days of party wrangling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S coalition government last night won the first round of a
parliamentary showdown with the opposition Liberal Democratic party, paving
the way for wholesale reforms to the corrupt political system.
A parliamentary committee voted in favour of the plans, ending days of
bitter wrangling between the seven-party coalition and a divided LDP.
The Tokyo stock exchange's Nikkei average recovered from Monday's 2.3 per
cent fall although investors remained cautious ahead of prime minister
Morihiro Hosokawa's visit to the US at the end of the week.
The committee vote means the four reform bills are now likely to gain
majority approval from what is set to be a stormy debate in the lower house
tomorrow. That is the biggest hurdle they face.
The bills will replace the present multi-seat constituency system, a
Japanese peculiarity blamed for encouraging politicians to use money and
influence to gain votes, with a mixture of single-seat constituencies and
proportional representation.
Lower house seats would be reduced from 511 to 500, of which 274 would come
from single-seat districts and 226 from proportional representation. The
reforms would also ban donations to individual politicians and parties would
have to disclose donations exceeding Y50,000 (Pounds 314) a year.
Yesterday's vote has opened a rift between younger LDP members eager for
reform and able to accept the compromises offered by Mr Hosokawa and older
parliamentarians who have spent years and millions of yen building power
bases and who fear losing their seats under the new system.
Several young LDP parliamentarians promised to vote for the government's
proposal tomorrow, heralding another wave of defections. Officials predicted
that between 20 and 30 LDP parliamentarians might defect to one of the
coalition reform groups.
Yesterday's vote follows an early morning breakdown in negotiations between
the government and an LDP paralysed by its internal divisions. An attempt to
reopen talks later yesterday morning got nowhere, leaving the LDP
outmanoeuvred by Mr Hosokawa's success. Tempers frayed as Mr Yohei Kono, the
LDP chairman, likened Mr Hosokawa to a 'banana salesman', an unusually
pungent insult by Japanese parliamentary standards.
If the reform bills clear the lower house by the end of the week, as is
likely, they should have enough time to pass through the upper house, the
final stage, by Mr Hosokawa's December 15 deadline. He had indicated he
would resign if political reform failed to get through parliament by the end
of the year. Unless the LDP employs delaying tactics in the upper house, it
does not look as if he will have to make that sacrifice.
Trade surplus, Page 4
Hosokawa on a tightrope, Page 7
Japanese stocks, Page 55
</TEXT>
<XX>
