<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Many insolvency practitioners may breach rules, report shows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE QUARTER of insolvency practitioners may be failing to meet their
obligations under the law, according to an inspection carried out over the
past few months by the government's Insolvency Service.
In monitoring visits to 147 of the UK's nearly 2,000 practitioners, 18 had
'significant compliance problems' which have triggered investigations by
their self-regulatory bodies.
A further 18 are believed to have exhibited less serious defaults which also
breach regulations.
The details are revealed in the 1992-93 annual report of the Insolvency
Service, an executive agency within the Department of Trade and Industry,
which was published yesterday.
They will intensify calls to strengthen regulation within the insolvency
profession, which has been subject to growing criticism over the past few
months.
Since the 1986 Insolvency Act, practitioners have been required to pass
exams and join a self-regulatory organisation, but little effort has been
made to screen those already practising.
The problems described by the Insolvency Service include failure to maintain
proper time records for their billings, misusing bank accounts and failure
to keep adequate financial and administrative records. A senior insolvency
service official said: 'The regulatory bodies still have some work to do to
meet the requirements in legislation.'
The report also shows that 11 insolvency practitioners and one manager were
under investigation at the end of the year, and that two practitioners and
two managers were convicted of criminal offences in the previous 12 months.
During the year, the service recommended withdrawal of the right to practise
from three of the insolvency practitioners which it regulates directly.
Mr Mark Homan of Price Waterhouse and president of the Society of
Practitioners of Insolvency, the leading trade body, said: 'Regrettably the
profession has a small number of black sheep but it has accomplished a lot
to clean up its act.'
Service fails to speed up, Page 13
</TEXT>
