<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Papers continue to lose sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WITH OFFICIAL newspaper circulation figures showing a pattern of continued
decline, the consultancy group Henley Centre warned yesterday that the
imposition of value added tax on newspapers and magazines could have a
'devastating' impact.
In the six months from May to October total sales of national dailies fell
by 1.69 per cent to just over 14m while the Sundays fell by 2.65 per cent to
15.8m.
Only three daily newspapers - The Sun, The Times and Today - increased sales
in the period.
The biggest loser was The Independent, which fell by 10.95 per cent to
333,647. Apart from Sunday Sport, which fell by 17.2 per cent, the worst
loser of the Sundays was The Independent on Sunday, which fell by 8 per cent
to 368,246. Only The Sunday Times and the Sunday Telegraph showed gains.
The Henley Centre argues that because newspaper circulations are already in
long-term decline 'VAT could send national newspapers into an inescapable
downward spiral'.
It believes the average price of dailies would rise from 30p to 34p and the
price of Sundays would rise from 62p to 70p. It says VAT at 17.5 per cent
would lead to a 6 per cent circulation loss for national dailies and 12 per
cent for Sunday titles.
'This is an overnight loss equivalent to that experienced by the industry
over the 1989-1992 recession,' says Henley, which based its forecasts on
econometric modelling work.
Henley believes publishers are likely to try to absorb some of the increased
costs but the effects would still be considerable. It forecasts a spiral of
declining circulations, higher prices and falling quality.
The relationship between price rises and circulation decreases has in the
past tended to show that a price rise of 10 per cent reduces sales by 6 per
cent.
The Treasury has estimated that VAT at 17.5 per cent on national newspapers
would yield Pounds 375m a year. Henley says this would be less than Pounds
250m because of price absorption.
The centre asks: 'Would the political fallout of VAT on national newspapers
be worth it for 0.5 per cent contribution to a public sector borrowing
requirement of Pounds 50bn?'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2711 Newspapers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MKTS  Sales.
</TP>
