<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Minister broadens contracting-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday added the management of vehicle fleets and
on-street parking to its programme of local authority contracting-out.
Mr Tony Baldry, the local government minister, said at a London conference
on market testing that the government was proposing that compulsory
competitive tendering for these areas should come in on April 1 1995. The
same would apply to security work six months later.
The additions mark the first broadening of competitive tendering for local
author-ities for more than a year.
The government plans to introduce the changes ahead of starting competitive
tendering in the Pounds 5bn white-collar services area, which will include
housing management, information technology and finance.
Tendering on some of these will start next summer but contracts will not
start until mid-1995.
Mr Baldry said compulsion should be the last resort in competitive
tendering. 'Local authorities should want to ensure that they get the best
value for local residents for the services they deliver without being
required to do so,' he added.
</TEXT>
