<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Derbyshire force fails audit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DERBYSHIRE police force has become the first to be refused a certificate
of efficiency for the second consecutive year.
Mr Geoffrey Dear, HM Inspector of Constabulary, said in a report released
yesterday that progress had been made, but without adequate resources
problems would continue to grow against a backdrop of rising crime.
Derbyshire is the only one of 43 forces in England and Wales to be refused
the certificate. Refusal is likely to have no effect in practice - although
the home secretary has power to refuse to release funds to the force or send
in a commissioner to run it.
Mr John Newing, chief constable of Derbyshire, said: 'The crucial issue is
one of a shortage of funds, a problem familiar to many police forces.' To
stay within budget, he said, the force had to keep 40 police officer posts
vacant and 26 civilian jobs had not been filled. He called on Mr Dear to
tell the Derbyshire Constabulary exactly what it needed to do to regain the
certificate.
Mr Dear said people had complained of long police response times, outbreaks
of burglary in residential streets and lack of visible patrolling in rural
areas. Last year crime in Derbyshire rose by 16 per cent, the second highest
rise of any force in the country.
Lord Ferrers, Home Office minister, said the force would be allocated an
extra Pounds 2m for measures such as additional vehicles and equipment. It
had also been given a set of measurable targets.
</TEXT>
