FT  17 NOV 93 / Error puts school in the spotlight
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SCHOOLS can shoot to the top of the league tables if someone at the
Department for Education makes a typing error.
Yesterday Chapel-en-le-Frith school in Stockport, Cheshire, enjoyed a
fleeting moment of fame in the nation's newsrooms. According to the league
tables it had only one pupil in the sixth form, but he or she was the new
Einstein - amassing 54 A-level points, equivalent to four grade As, one B
and one C.
The school's headmaster had an even better story - the education department
had given the accolade of top A-level performer to a school which did not
even have a sixth form.
Officials said external contractors had made a computer error, which will be
corrected when booklets of the results are distributed to schools.
Five other schools briefly benefited from high-performing, but non-existent,
A-level candidates.
