<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / IBM offshoot with a future to look after: In Hampshire, no
one thinks they are prolonging the death agonies of a hopeless case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNDER THE bonnet of Aston Martin's new DB7 sports car, which enters
production in April next year, is evidence of IBM Havant's determination to
prove that it can make its own way in the world.
The electronic engine management system, key to the car's performance, has
been designed by Zytek Automotive but it will be manufactured in volumes of
up to 700 a year by the Hampshire-based manufacturing and development
division of International Business Machines - the world's largest computer
maker.
The manufacturing deal is one of about a dozen that Havant has struck in the
past six months with customers outside IBM and which seem likely to
guarantee Havant's survival, with the jobs of the 1,500 people it employs.
Havant was earlier this year redesignated as an 'industrial business
centre', owned by IBM but controlled by local management and with its own
profit and loss responsibility.
It was one of four European plants that the troubled computer giant had
deemed 'surplus to requirements' and which had to make a satisfactory profit
on their own or face closure.
IBM has been losing money heavily in the past two years, hit globally by
recession and price wars in the computer business. It has been restructuring
on a grand scale.
In retrospect it seems the threat to Havant was more apparent than real. The
facility's main role is the manufacture of hard disk drives and controllers
for IBM's small computer systems.
This year it will make nearly 1m hard disk drives for IBM. Next year, with
volumes boosted by a contract from the US disk drive manufacturer Western
Digital, the total is likely to be 2m.
For some components Havant is IBM's only source worldwide. This year, for
example, it will turn out more than 1m flexible electronic circuits,
essential technical wizardry for tiny, portable electronic gadgets. It will
also make about 4,000 memory sub-systems for IBM's mid-range computers.
Its senior executives see themselves managing a vigorous business rather
than prolonging the death agonies of a hopeless case. Mr Ken Wilkie, chief
executive, was in charge of logistical support for IBM UK's manufacturing
operations while Ms Catherine Marsden, head of marketing, worked directly
with Mr Nick Temple, IBM UK chief executive, on his plans to restructure the
British subsidiary.
This year, Mr Wilkie said, turnover would amount to about Pounds 500,000, of
which 15 per cent would be derived from work undertaken for companies
outside IBM.
Havant has established its own business brand - 'Xyratex' - to distinguish
its engineering work for outside customers.
Offerings will include design, manufacturing and full support services
including logistics, quality assurance and laboratory facilities. A key
selling point, Mr Wilkie believes, is its ability to control the product
manufacturing process from design and development to delivery and service.
The Xyratex name was created by the style consultancy Interbrand.
There is a lighter side to Xyratex's work. Among its creations is the 'Note
Station', a system it developed for the Music Writer company, which prints
on demand the complete score of a musical work - transposing it into any key
the customer wants along the way. It also makes Winners All, a gambling
machine.
</TEXT>
