<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / More pass in vocational courses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PUPILS taking vocational qualifications, which assess practical skills such
as dressmaking and photography, obtained superior results to those taking
academic subjects, the government's league tables show.
At Marshalls Park School in Romford, Essex, for example, all 232 of the
school's 15-year-olds were entered for GCSE examinations and the City &amp;
Guilds Diploma of Vocational Education (Foundation). Twenty eight per cent
achieved five or more grades at GCSE while 93 per cent achieved their
vocational qualification.
Mr Cedrick Hendricks, headmaster of the comprehensive school, said: 'It is
not that vocational qualifications are easier than academic ones. They are
just different.
'The vocational qualification, which is an umbrella qualification, is made
up of several units in subjects like law, technology and administration.
'Some of these units can be achieved after six or seven-week courses. It can
be easier to motivate students on these shorter courses, which may, for
example, include visits to the law courts. In addition it is easier for
teachers to make sure that pupils are on target.'
Vocational qualifications, which assess a person's practical competence to
do a task, have been offered in a small number of schools for some years.
They have long been regarded by parents and employers, however, as a poor
relation to academic qualifications. This is a perception which the
government is seeking to change. For example, General National Vocational
Qualifications (GNVQs) are being offered to students older than 16 in
England and Wales as a vocational equivalent to A-levels. National
Vocational Qualifications (NVQs) are available for people in work.
Both parents and employers have expressed anxiety about the new
qualifications. Mr Hendricks said when two years ago his school decided to
offer vocational qualifications there was resistance from parents.
Mr Hendricks said parents were starting to see their validity. 'They see
that there is a certificate of achievement and that it can contribute
towards a further qualification.'
Less than 10 per cent of the 5,200 schools in England and Wales offered
vocational qualifications in 1993 - with numbers varying from all the pupils
in a school to just one or two.
The schools with most entrants were Marshalls Park School, Knutsford High
School in Cheshire, Thomas Bennett Community College in Tilgate, West
Sussex, and Moseley School, West Midlands.
The two awarding bodies for pre-16-year-olds are BTEC and City &amp; Guilds. The
organisations have different origins and are technically in competition with
each other. BTEC is newer than City &amp; Guilds, which has its origins in the
livery companies that provided training for artisans and craftsmen.
</TEXT>
