<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Manchester council attacks truancy figures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRUANCY figures released today shed fresh light on the extent of the
problem, but there is still controversy about their accuracy.
The figures have been fiercely contested by some local authorities.
Labour-controlled Manchester is home to the 'worst' school for truancy on
education department figures, with more than one in five pupils absent
without leave at any one time.
But the authority rejected the government's figures, which showed that it
suffered the worst truancy in the country with pupils skipping 6.4 per cent
of lessons on aver-age.
Describing the figures as 'spurious', the authority said Manchester had
24,450 pupils, while the education department's figures implied that it had
only 13,333. Criteria could vary between authorities and even from school to
school.
For example, much parentally condoned absence might be truancy by any
reason-able definition, but might still be regarded as authorised absences
by some schools.
Education department plans to publish figures for authorised absences next
year might only emphasise areas badly hit by influenza epidemics.
The worst records at primary school level were suffered by the London
authorities of Lambeth, Newham, Kensington and Chelsea, and Tower Hamlets,
all of which saw 40 per cent or more of pupils play truant at least once.
Nationally, pupils who have played truant at some time amount to 12 per
cent.
Truancy and deprivation correlate closely, as the main table for local
education authorities shows.
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, has said truancy is 'a contributory
factor in juvenile crime'.
He pointed to Cambridge University research which showed that 48 per cent of
young offenders were truants.
But a government-funded study by the University of North London showed no
definite link with crime, although it suggested that the scale of the
problem was even greater than the government's figures showed, with 30.5 per
cent of children playing truant at least once in their last two years of
compulsory schooling.
The North London survey found that the greatest cause was dissatisfaction
with lessons, cited by two-thirds of truants.
One in five did so played truant to avoid particular lessons, with physical
education, games, French, maths and English the most unpopular subjects.
Disapproval of parents and teachers was the most powerful control on
truants, suggesting that 'school ethos is the critical variable'.
