<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Minister commends Welsh results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE PUPILS in Wales achieved five or more GCSE passes with A to C grades
this year than in 1992, with the proportion rising from a third to 37 per
cent.
Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, yesterday described this performance as a
'marked improvement'. He said there had also been an increase in the
proportion of 15-year-olds entering an examination at the GCSE or CoE level,
with the numbers rising to more than 19 in 20. Of these pupils 94 per cent,
a rise of 1 percentage point, passed at least one examination.
The examination results for Wales, which are published today, show that the
proportion of pupils attaining five or more GCSE passes with A to C grades
was lowest in Mid Glamorgan. The county, which includes the towns of Merthyr
Tydfil and Bridgend, scored only 29 per cent compared with the highest score
of 44 per cent in the south-western rural county of Dyfed. The second
highest score, of 40 per cent, was returned by another rural county, Powys.
At A and AS level, Mid Glamorgan was also bottom on a new measure of
achievement converting grades into points, while Powys came top of this
category.
Overall, 14 per cent of Welsh pupils achieved points equivalent to gaining A
level passes with A to C grades, and 6 per cent achieved the equivalent of
at least three grade A results. Students at all Wales' further education and
sixth form colleges achieved no more points on average than the schools in
Mid Glamorgan.
Among independent schools, pupils at St Michael's School in Dyfed scored 100
per cent in achieving at least five GCSE passes with A to C grades, but only
26 pupils at the school entered. In the principality as a whole the most
successful independent schools at this level included Howell's School in
South Glamorgan (95 per cent from a total of 79 pupils) and Monmouth School
in Gwent (95 per cent, 93 pupils).
The most successful state schools at GCSE level were Cardiff High School (72
per cent, 160 pupils); Gyfun Bro Hyrddin at Carmarthen (71 per cent, 83
pupils); and Bishopston Comprehensive, Swansea (67 per cent, 184 pupils).
At A level the average points score for all Welsh schools was 14. Among
independent schools results were highly variable. The highest point scores
were achieved by Haberdashers Monmouth School for Girls, Gwent (23); St
Michael's School, Dyfed (22); and St Gerards School Trust, Gwynedd (22). The
grant-maintained Stanwell Comprehensive School in South Glamorgan scored 21.
Among state schools at A level the most successful were Caereinion High
School at Llanfair Caereinion, Powys (22); Denbigh High School in Clwyd
(20); and Croesyceiliog Comprehensive at Cwmbran (19).
Of colleges, the best A level results on the points basis were scored by
Gorseinon College in West Glamorgan, with 306 students achieving an average
score of 16 points.
</TEXT>
