<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Close attention key to academic results
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Charters School in Berkshire (above), the third-placed local
authority-maintained comprehensive at A-level in a recent FT survey, thinks
close attention is the key to results. The school, sceptical of league
tables, concentrates on the National Record of Achievement. This presents
pupils with folders in which all their achievements can be assessed. Keeping
the folders up to date obliges teachers to meet pupils individually and
regularly.
St Paul's school in Barnes, west London, uses tutor groups in a similar
approach. Every boy keeps the same tutor throughout his career and the
school says its teachers can build an enviable ability to spot boys who have
the most potential, and those who need the most help.
