<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Top ministers back us on Europe, says CBI: Hunt grilled on
burden of social costs; Delors urged not to destroy jobs; Davies calls for
tight spending control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry yesterday claimed the support of the
government's three main economic ministers for its campaign for European
economic integration.
Sir Michael Angus, president of the CBI, spoke out after Mr David Hunt,
employment secretary, aligned himself firmly with the pro-European views
expressed on Monday by Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor, and Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary.
Sir Michael said the three ministers' speeches to the CBI conference in
Harrogate showed that 'their views on Europe are in parallel with ours'. CBI
leaders have been increasingly critical of the government's 'negative'
approach to Europe, which some believe has damaged British economic
prospects.
Mr Hunt told the CBI conference in Harrogate that his speech to last month's
Conservative party conference in Blackpool had been wrongly interpreted as
an attack on European integration. 'My personal commitment to this country's
place at the heart of Europe is central to my own personal political
philosophy,' he said.
Mr Hunt told delegates: 'Although we hear what you say about a single or
common currency for Europe, we are focusing on the practical objectives of
promoting economic recovery and economic convergence among the countries of
Europe.'
He said a single currency 'is not merely an economic policy - it would be an
undertaking of enormous political significance as well'.
Mr Hunt was careful to echo the vision of a decentralised, free-market and
free-trading European Union set out by the prime minister at last month's
European summit in Brussels.
He said later, however, that he remained committed to 'the ultimate
objective' of a single European currency. In spite of the consensus on
Europe, Mr Hunt faced trenchant criticism from CBI leaders of the burden of
social costs on industry.
Mr Bryan Rigby, chairman of the CBI's employment committee, said employers
were worried about reports that more of the cost of maternity and sick pay
was to be shifted to business.
'We don't expect to find this government putting extra burdens upon us
whilst criticising others for doing the same,' he said.
Tax reliefs which expire at the end of the year when the Business Expansion
Scheme winds up should be transferred into new reliefs for private
investment in private companies, the CBI said yesterday.
Mr Richard Brucciani, chairman of the CBI Small Business Council, said:
'Unless we change the way we do some things in this country, smaller
businesses cannot deliver, cannot be the engine of recovery'.
The demand for tax relief for people investing in growing business is part
of a search for funding diversity. The CBI is concerned that small companies
are too reliant on overdrafts.
Mr Richard Head, chief manager of National Westminster Bank, said this was
why banks offered small businesses term loans for up to 20 years. The
clearing banks, he added, had Pounds 43bn of loans outstanding to companies
with annual turnovers of less than Pounds 1m.
</TEXT>
