<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Disabled to protest at work changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DISABLED PEOPLE will today protest against changes in government programmes
that assist them in employment, Lisa Wood writes.
They will lobby Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, who is at a two-day
conference on how Training and Enterprise Councils - which deliver
government training programmes in England and Wales - can best assist people
with special needs.
From next April, the Access to Work scheme will replace the six existing
programmes, costing Pounds 14m a year, that help the disabled.
The scheme will seek to help more people, but employers will be asked to
contribute towards assistance for disabled employees. At present, they
receive full government grants to adapt their premises. The government is
also proposing to limit the amount of help any individual can receive.
The Royal National Institute for the Blind said yesterday it welcomed new
flexibilities in Access for Work, but it was concerned that charges being
imposed on employers would be a disincentive to the employment of disabled
people.
