<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Sky TV opens broadside to sink decoder pirates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SKY TELEVISION is believed to have adopted anti-piracy measures early
yesterday in an attempt to disable unauthorised decoder cards.
The satellite broadcaster altered the stream of data from its satellite
system to its subscribers in trying to prevent the use of pirate cards.
Yesterday Mr Chris McKenzie, general manager at Sky, said he had no comment.
Last month Sky, in which Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has a stake,
made it clear that it intended to take every legal and technical action it
could against the pirates.
Mr David Lyons, whose company Satellite Decoding Systems imported illicit
decoder cards from the Republic of Ireland to the UK, said that his cards
had not been affected by Sky's latest action.
Mr Lyons has given legal undertakings that he will neither advertise nor
sell pirate cards in the UK.
He has returned to Ireland where he concentrates on selling Sky cards to
continental Europe.
Mr Lyons said yesterday that he was offering, or was about to offer, pirate
cards for French satellite service Canal Plus, Belgian channel FilmNet and
Scandinavian channels TV3 and TV1000.
Recently the Scandinavian channels have taken action against Mr Chris Cary
and Hi-Tech Innovation of Camberley who had been supplying pirate cards.
TV3 obtained an injunction against Mr Cary and notified the police.
