<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Budget 1993: Food industry split on VAT lobbying aims - Guy
de Jonquieres picks through a menu of nutritional anomalies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK subsidiary of Nestle, the world's biggest food manufacturer, made an
embarrassing discovery this week. It found it was lobbying the Treasury to
adopt two contradictory policies in the Budget.
With one hand Nestle was supporting industry efforts to ward off any
increase in value added tax on about 80 per cent of food products which are
zero-rated. With the other it was backing a campaign - from which it has
withdrawn - to abolish zero-rating on all but fresh food.
Nestle is not alone in its confusion about Britain's complicated system of
taxing food and drink, the complexities of which have split the industry -
and many companies - down the middle.
Most types of food are classified as necessities and carry a zero rate of
VAT. All other food and drink products carry VAT at the standard 17.5 per
cent rate. The categories are a relic of purchase tax, abolished in 1973,
which discriminated against 'luxury' consumer products and services.
Food manufacturers complain that two-tier VAT is riddled with anomalies.
Gingerbread men dipped in chocolate carry VAT at 17.5 per cent, while
gingerbread women dipped in caramel are zero-rated. Chocolate-coated
biscuits and shelled nuts are taxed at the standard rate, but
chocolate-filled biscuits and unshelled nuts go VAT-free.
Rapid product innovation has aggravated the discrepancies. When the tax
rules were first devised the only snacks were potato-based or produced by
'swelling' cereals. These still carry standard VAT. Newer products, however,
such as tortilla chips which are not made from potato or swollen cereals,
are zero-rated.
Manufacturers say such inequities - exaggerated by the rise in the standard
VAT rate from 8 per cent to 17.5 per cent in the past 20 years  - distort
the market.
Efforts by Customs and Excise to tinker - usually by challenging products'
zero-rated status - have stirred up legal and political opposition and have
sometimes failed.
After struggling last year to standardise VAT on snacks Customs abandoned
the attempt as hopeless and its move to slap standard-rate VAT on Jaffa
cakes was defeated in the courts. More recently, the ending of zero-rating
on freshly-squeezed orange juice was criticised by MPs.
Many food manufacturers believe the system is absurd but they cannot agree
on what should replace it. Most dare not press too hard for reform, for fear
that reform would involve ending zero-rating.
This view has shaped pre-Budget lobbying by the Food and Drink Federation,
the umbrella organisation of the main industry associations. The federation
has told the Treasury that the end of zero-rating would lead to higher
inflation, job losses and lower industry profits.
This stance has been broadly supported by the industry, but it has been
criticised by some manufacturers of products such as snacks, confectionery,
soft drinks and ice cream, on which 17.5 per cent VAT is charged.
Mr Keith Nightingale, director-general of the Snacks, Nuts and Crisps
Manufacturers Association, said: 'The federation seems to be putting all its
effort into preserving the status quo and doing nothing for all of us who
pay the standard VAT rate.'
Several confectionery manufacturers belonging to the Biscuit, Cake,
Chocolate and Confectionery Alliance have broken ranks and launched a
campaign to have VAT extended to all processed foods at a rate of 8 per
cent. That, they say, would end discrimination without reducing the Pounds
1.6bn a year the exchequer receives from VAT on food.
Companies backing the campaign include Cadbury, Mars and - until this week -
Nestle. Although their proposals suit Rowntree, Nestle's confectionery
subsidiary, many of the group's other businesses such as instant coffee,
yoghurts and frozen food would be penalised.
Similar conflicts of interest beset other industry associations. Some ice
cream manufacturers want a lower VAT rate but Unilever, the industry leader,
is keen to avoid endangering the zero rate on its other products.
One option would be to zero-rate all food. As well as costing the Treasury
revenue, however, that would require a special exemption from European
Community rules, which Brussels would be reluctant to grant.
Under EU rules Britain could charge as little as 5 per cent VAT on food. But
this would also cut Treasury revenue unless it was applied to some or all of
the food products which are currently zero-rated.
Any extension of VAT, even at a relatively low rate, on food would, however,
be politically unpopular.
Given the unpalatable alternatives, the betting must be that the present
system, for all its faults, will survive the Budget largely intact.
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
SPOT THE DIFFERENCE
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
STANDARD RATE (17.5 PER CENT)
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Gingerbread figure with head dipped in chocolate
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Salted or roasted shelled nuts
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Potato crisps, potato sticks, potato puffs and similar products
made from potato derivatives: savoury food products made by
swelling of cereals or cereals product eg potato crisps, popcorn,
Hula-Hoops, Skips, Wotsits and Quavers
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Chocolate biscuits
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Ice cream, including ice cream sold for desserts and table use,
Ice lollies, frozen yoghurt suitable for immediate consumption
when frozen, eg soft enough to be eaten with a spoon
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Confectionery; including crystallised fruit, compressed fruit bars,
cereal bars, banana chips
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Puffed cereal product marketed as a snack
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
sandwich sold from kiosk in amusement park
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
ZERO-RATED
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Gingerbread figure with head dipped in chocolate
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Nuts in shell, unsalted or unroasted nuts even though shelled
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Any snack product not covered by potato criterion and not made
by the process of swelling cereals or cereal products eg Tortilla
chips, corn chips, mini biscuits, Twiglets, savoury product made from
biscuit regardless of shape, appearance or fillings.  Dried fruit
snacks, pork scratchings
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Plain biscuits, sugar-coated biscuits and biscuits containing chocolate
as a sandwich layer
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Yoghurt, mousse and similar products which are not ice cream but
are prepared and marketed for identical use
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Meringues, toffeee apples, ethnic delicacies
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Puffed cereal product marketed as a breakfast cereal
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
Sandwich sold from kiosk in public park
 --------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
