<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Police may be forced to co-operate on Nadir
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRUSTEE in bankruptcy to Mr Asil Nadir, the fugitive businessman, is
considering using court orders against senior police officials who, he
claims, have failed to co-operate in his efforts to trace assets.
The proposed action by Mr Neil Cooper, a partner with accountants Robson
Rhodes, came after refusals by the police to answer allegations that they
were aware of the location of some of Mr Nadir's assets.
Meanwhile, the Crown Prosecution Service said yesterday that it had decided
not to bring a case against Mr Nadir in connection with allegations that he
had attempted to bribe a senior judge.
It said it had concluded that there was 'no credible evidence' to support
suggestions that Mr Nadir had attempted to pay Pounds 3.5m to Mr Justice
Tucker, who was scheduled to hear his fraud trial last month.
The CPS said it had decided not to continue the action following receipt of
a report from the Metropolitan Police last Friday at the end of a 'lengthy
investigation'.
The CPS added that Mr Michael Francis and Ms Wendy Welsher, who are believed
to be in northern Cyprus, had made the original allegations of a conspiracy
involving Mr Tucker, Mr Nadir, Mr Anthony Scrivener QC, who is Mr Nadir's
lawyer, and Mr Wyn Jones, suspended assistant commissioner of the
Metropolitan Police.
Ms Welsher admitted a year ago to have held a painting valued at Pounds
400,000 which is claimed by Mr Nadir's trustees and is now believed to have
been removed from the UK.
The police had contacted Ms Welsher but Mr Cooper said that they refused to
provide him with any information on her or the painting's whereabouts during
the past year.
Under section 366 of the 1986 Insolvency Act, the police could be forced to
answer questions.
Those covered by the court orders could include Detective Chief
Superintendent Tom Glendinning and Mr George Staple, head of the Serious
Fraud Office.
Mr Nadir was due to face trial last month on 13 charges of theft and false
accounting involving Pounds 34m, but he broke his bail conditions and fled
to northern Cyprus in May this year.
Mr Nadir yesterday accused the British authorities of perverting the course
of justice and said he intended to sue the SFO, the director of public
prosecutions, Scotland Yard and others.
</TEXT>
