<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Bidders for BR to be given a dry run
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POTENTIAL bidders for privatised British Rail routes will be invited to take
part in 'shadow negotiations' with the Office of Passenger Rail Franchising
early next year.
The office has been set up by the government to handle the franchising of
BR's routes and to monitor the performance of franchisees.
Mr Roger Salmon, franchising director, said yesterday that the purpose of
the negotiations was to explain to the bidding teams how the franchising
system works and to allow the office to refine its own proposals.
One of the main aims of the franchising office is to establish agreements
which provide commercial incentives for companies involved in the new system
and which minimise the scope for legal disputes.
Mr Salmon said: 'We have devised a 'no-fault' incentive system which keeps
the lawyers in their place.'
Franchisees will be paid according to the quality and reliability of the
train service, while Railtrack, the company set up to own the track and
signalling, will be able to charge more for providing a high quality of
service to the operator.
Mr Salmon, a former corporate financier with NM Rothschild, the merchant
bank, is to spend the next few weeks explaining the details of the
franchising system at a series of conferences and presentations.
'There is a lot of the detail which is important,' he said. 'Only when we
get that into the public domain will the big players sit up and get
talking.'
Invitations to tender are expected to go out next October and the first
private operators will take over in the spring of 1995. About 50 private
companies and 30 teams of British Rail managers have expressed an interest.
The capital needed to take over rail operations is not large because
equipment will be leased or rented. But bidders will be required to provide
bonds to reimburse season ticket holders in the event of the company
folding. They may also have to provide guarantees of 'good behaviour'.
Mr Salmon described the move to franchising as 'the biggest change in the
railway system, including nationalisation' but said he did not expect
large-scale changes in the physical shape of the network. Companies taking
over franchises to run British Rail routes will pay more to use the track at
peak times, Railtrack, the company set up to manage British Rail track and
signalling, said yesterday.
Charges will depend in part on the type and the number of trains run, wear
and tear on the track and the cost of any improvements and investment in the
line.
Details of how Railtrack will charge for its services were unveiled at the
formal launch of the company in London.
Railtrack will spend the next few months devising access agreements for its
future customers; acquiring formal ownership of 10,000 miles of track, 2,500
stations and 90,000 bridges; and taking on responsibility for the 22,000
tenants in British Rail property.
It will also investigate ways of involving private sector finance to help
fund modernisation of track and signalling.
Safety will be monitored by a safety directorate which will be part of
Railtrack but which, Railtrack said, would be kept, 'as far as possible',
separate from its commercial arm.
When Railtrack formally takes over control of BR's infrastructure on April 1
it will have 12,000 staff ranging from signalmen to business controllers.
Track and signals will be grouped in 10 geographical zones.
</TEXT>
