<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / RSPB calls for law to safeguard forests after privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT must have powers to buy back forests if they are not managed
to high environmental standards after privatisation, according to Europe's
largest wildlife charity.
The Royal Society for the Protection of Birds also wants Forestry Commission
properties to be excluded from privatisation if their sale would jeopardise
the wood-processing industry, local jobs and communities, public access and
recreation, or wildlife conservation, research and education. These are the
principal components of the government's current policy of 'multi-purpose'
forestry.
The RSPB, which has 870,000 members including at least 40 in the Commons and
Lords, is proposing a private member's bill as part of a campaign to
highlight what it sees as the difficulties of safeguarding environmental
values in the event of a sale of Britain's forests. It will be lobbying MPs
who come top of the private members' ballot on November 25.
The charity, which itself manages an estate of about 190,000 acres, has been
successful in getting two previous private member's bills on to the statute
books, in 1991 and 1992. If its latest bill were to succeed it would upset
any privatisation plans by making purchases less attractive, particularly
for buyers interested only in timber exploitation.
A review group of civil servants, due to report to ministers early next
year, is considering options for the privatisation of all or part of the
2.8m-acre Forestry Commission estate. Although privatisation is favoured by
some Tory MPs, it is opposed by the majority of interested parties from wood
processors to environmental groups.
The bill would enable the government to buy back land after five years if it
was not being managed to the environmental standards currently laid down by
the Forestry Commission. It would also require all privatised land to be
subject to a management plan. If the new owners failed to implement the plan
the government would be able to do so.
Mr Roger Turner, the RSPB's forestry policy officer, said Forest Enterprise,
which manages the Forestry Commission's land, follows government policy of
ensuring there is a variety of old and young trees and dense and open
woodland of the kind required by different species of birds and plants. For
conservation purposes it fells some trees earlier or later than it would if
it were seeking the maximum return from the timber.
He said: 'We're concerned that in virtually all the options for transferring
ownership, if the forest goes into the hands of individuals or organisations
who wish to pursue a single purpose, like making money from the timber, then
these requirements will not be met.'
The RSPB estimates that it would cost the government an additional Pounds
51.55m a year in grants and administration to maintain current conservation
standards on Forestry Commission land and develop its environmental
potential in the event of a wholesale transfer to the private sector. This
would compare with a book value of Pounds 1.7bn for the estate and
predictions that it could fetch as little as Pounds 500m on the market. 'It
would be a short-term gain for a long-term cost,' said Mr Turner.
Last week three former executives of the Forestry Commission said additional
expenditure would amount to Pounds 44m a year in 2000, while the government
would be losing Pounds 20m a year in timber sales.
</TEXT>
<XX>
