<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / NZ poll stalemate broken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WELLINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE National party early today picked up the crucial Waitaki seat from
Labour in the official recount of New Zealand's election, giving it a
slender majority in the new parliament.
The win gave the party, headed by prime minister Jim Bolger, 50 seats in the
99-seat single-chamber parliament and Labour 45, with two minor parties, the
Alliance and New Zealand First, having two seats each.
But opposition parties were expected to demand that Mr Bolger's government
provide a Speaker, who may have to use his casting vote to support the
government on crucial matters.
There were two marginal seats left to be declared, but political analysts
thought they were unlikely to cause an upset.
Labour's narrow loss of Waitaki was the first change since the official
recount began in the cliffhanger election, held on November 6. But a number
of seats are held with tiny majorities and some defeated candidates say they
will seek judicial reviews or electoral petitions, which could mean that the
final outcome may not be known till January.
</TEXT>
