<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Papua New Guinea exchange
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Papua New Guinea could get its own stock exchange by the second half of
1994, the government announced yesterday, Nikki Tait writes from Sydney.
The exchange would be based on Australian Stock Exchange rules and its
formation would be subject to a minimum level of interest from brokers and
dealers. However, 'Once a minimum of five members have agreed to participate
the exchange will open for business,' Sir Julius Chan, PNG's finance and
planning minister, said yesterday.
The proposal emerged in the course the finance minister's budget speech, and
Sir Julius added that taxation reforms were being introduced which would
facilitate transactions on a PNG stock exchange. Reforms to the companies
act and to foreign exchange regulations would be finalised by the next
session of parliament.
