<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 93 / Smith lays basis for closer Labour ties with industry:
Party's commitment to manufacturing given warm reception by CBI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, the Labour leader, yesterday laid the foundations of a closer
relationship with the Confederation of British Industry by stressing the
opposition's commitment to manufacturing industry.
Mr Smith largely avoided controversial issues in a warmly received speech at
the organisation's conference in Harrogate designed to convince business
leaders they have nothing to fear from a Labour government.
Aides said his intention, as the first Labour leader to address the CBI, was
to prepare the ground for the launch of the party's industrial policy
document next year, which will set out detailed proposals for partnerships
between government departments and business.
Labour officials say business leaders have welcomed many of the party's
emerging proposals, although there is concern about plans for worker
directors being drawn up by Mr Robin Cook, the party's industry spokesman.
CBI members gave Mr Smith a sustained ovation, which observers contrasted
with the more restrained applause accorded cabinet ministers on Monday. 'The
message that came across was that he is passionately committed to
manufacturing industry,' one delegate said. Mr David Hunt, employment
secretary, sought to undermine the impact of Mr Smith's appearance by
drawing attention to the omission from his speech of any reference to the
party's commitment to a 35-hour, four-day working week.
Mr Hunt said Mr Smith had failed to request an opt-out from the election
manifesto of the European socialist group, which contains the commitment.
However, delegates also responded warmly to Mr Smith's stress on Labour's
commitment to improvements in training, education and the potential for
partnerships between government departments and business.
Mr Smith sought to exploit divisions between some business leaders and the
government by endorsing criticism of the Conservative party's 'negative
approach' expressed by Mr Howard Davies, the CBI director-general. 'Such a
posture can seriously damage our interests. It is ironic that those who
promised to put Britain at the heart of Europe have caused us to be
marginalised in crucial areas of decision making,' he said.
Mr Smith warned delegates that British business would have to live with the
social chapter of the European Union's Maastricht treaty, in spite of the
government's decision to opt out.
He said the opt-out meant British ministers would 'leave the room' when
employment issues were discussed, leaving the other 11 countries to
determine policies 'which almost inexorably will come to be applied, not
just to British companies operating in Europe, but to all companies
operating in Britain'.
Mr Smith called for an early cut in interest rates to boost recovery, and
urged the government to avoid threatening the recovery by imposing tax
increases in the budget. He also called on ministers to drop plans to
increase the proportion of sick pay met by employers.
However, his main aim was to draw a sharp contrast between Labour's support
for manufacturing and the low level of investment in industry since the
Conservatives came to power in 1979.
'I have always believed passionately that Britain's prosperity depends upon
the creation of a dynamic and competitive economy, built on the bedrock of a
strong manufacturing sector,' he said.
Sir Michael Angus, CBI president, said there was 'a lot in the speech which
we would agree with, and with which our members would agree', but wide
differences remained on public spending and the social chapter of the EU's
Maastricht treaty.
CBI reports, Page 11
Observer, Page 25
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
