<PROFILE>_AN-DKPCNAGPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931116
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 93 / FT Traveller, Barcelona (19): Key facts for visitors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUSTIN WEBSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CURRENCY:
The peseta remains in the EMS but has undergone a series of devaluations
which has resulted in a 20 per cent drop in its value against the D-Mark in
the past year and a half.
All the leading banks - found concentrated around Placa Catalunya and
Passeig de Gracia - operate 'cambios' for changing money, based on the
official rates of the Bank of Spain that day with varying commission
structures.
On Las Ramblas and around the cathedral independent cambios offer 'no
commission'. However their rates, except for extremely large amounts,
generally make it preferable to pay the commission at the banks.
Leading credit cards such as Visa, Access/Mastercard and American Express
are accepted at most shops, restaurants and hotels.
TELEPHONES:
The international dialing code for Barcelona is 343. To make an
international call dial 07 and wait for a high pitched tone before
continuing. To dial anywhere else in Spain you need to add a regional code
such as 91 for Madrid or 95 for Seville.
Public telephones operate both with coins and with cards, which can be
bought at newspaper kiosks which can be found on most streets in the centre.
International calls are much more expensive than in most EC countries, while
local calls within the city are extremely cheap.
TIME:
Spanish time is one hour ahead of Britain (Greenwich Mean Time) and six
hours ahead of New York, except in the four weeks in early autumn from late
September when the Spanish clocks go back at the end of summertime to the
same time as Britain.
HOTELS:
Being a city which is increasingly designed for the business tourist, the
easiest time to find a hotel room is in August when prices drop by about 50
per cent.
Package tourists generally stay on the Costa Brava and visit the city for
the day. The busiest times are when a big trade exhibition is taking place
at the Fira, which last year registered 1.6m visitors.
The biggest were for food at the end of February, consumer electronics in
the middle of September and tourism in the second half of April. Plenty of
hotel rooms are now on offer, but it is worth booking in advance at these
times of the year if you have a specific hotel in mind.
RESTAURANTS:
The city has thousands of bars. Many of these serve a lunchtime menu which
includes bread and wine and can vary from the excellent to the grim. In the
top bracket there are a number of restaurants with one Michelin star, but
only one, Neichel on the Avinguda de Pedralbes, which has two.
It is worth booking a few days in advance for the more expensive
restaurants, although the recession has reduced pressure on places.
CLUBS:
The Circulo Ecuestre, Balmes 169, is one of the best-known among the
business community. It is for members only but the British Chamber of
Commerce (317-3220/3120) holds a lunch there on the first Thursday of every
month which is open to visiting businessmen and women who contact the
chamber in advance.
One of the most popular business lunching spots, almost the equivalent to a
club amongst the financial and commercial elite, is the restaurant
Finisterre (Avinguda Diagonal, 469).
TIPPING:
The guidelines on tipping are not clearly established. In the top bracket
restaurants and hotels 5 per cent is considered correct. In bars and taxis
there is no obligation to tip.
AIRPORT:
The redesigned and expanded national and international airport of El Prat
del Llobregat is seven miles from the centre of the city to the south.
Iberia has just announced that it is to become the centre of its European
operations. Air Europe and SAS have both recently entered the market.
Iberia operates a shuttle service to Madrid which runs from early morning to
late evening.
The airport itself provides information on flight arrivals (Tel: 478 5000)
but it is necessary to call each airline for information on departures
(Iberia in Barcelona: 301 3993).
TO AND FROM THE AIRPORT:
It normally takes between 15 minutes and half an hour to get to the airport
from the centre by car. An airport bus runs every 15 minutes from Placa
Catalunya, at a cost of Pts 400, which takes half an hour. The times to be
wary of are when the morning and evening rush hours combine with some other
event, for example one of Barcelona Football Club's important games of the
season, or the beginning of a long weekend in the middle of the skiing or
mushroom-picking seasons (the latter in the autumn). Trains run regularly
from Sants station.
PUBLIC TRANSPORT:
The centre is well-served by the metro system which is also cheap. A
tarjeta, a ticket for 10 journeys costs Pts 560. The same applies for the
buses, which have a separate tarjeta.
Within the city itself it is sometimes preferable to use the Ferrocarrils de
la Generalitat, the regional suburban network, when for instance, you need
to go further up the Tibidabo mountain than the metro. An old,
well-preserved tram operates from the end of the line at Avinguda del
Tibidabo for the last leg to the top.
The city has 11,300 black and yellow taxis. A green light on the roof and a
sign on the windscreen saying 'Libre' or 'Lliure' indicates they are free
for hire.
Six trains depart daily to Madrid from Sants station which take eight or
nine hours and cost Pts 3,800 to Pts 11,000 one way. The overnight sleeper
to Paris from the newly-renovated Estacio de Franca leaves at 2100 and costs
Pts 14,800.
