<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 93 / FT Traveller, Barcelona (15): It helps to learn the native
tongue - Language / While not essential, some knowledge of Catalan - spoken
in and around Barcelona - is an advantage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUSTIN WEBSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the most popular television programmes on the Catalan language
channel of TV3, following the common format of an open debate, is called
'Right to Speak'. One moment which attracted a kind of awed gratitude
recently occurred when a Japanese couple among the audience joined in and
spoke in Catalan.
This is the other side of what those who speak Castilian - the main language
of Spain - can sometimes find a frustration when they visit Barcelona. A
Castilian-speaking Frenchman who came to the city to research a cultural
topic recently was amazed to find that some of the books published by the
Generalitat (the autonomous government) appeared in both Catalan and
English, neither of which he understood.
Catalans can occasionally be obstinate about sticking to their native tongue
if they feel that it is not being accorded due respect. Alternatively, they
can often be more receptive to someone speaking Catalan. So though, for most
practical purposes, for foreigners there is no necessity to understand or
speak Catalan, rather than Castilian, there are advantages.
The language itself has a more abrupt, less inflected sound than Castilian.
Both are derived from Latin, but it seems that Catalan comes from a later
form of it, as did Provencal, the language spoken on the other side of the
Pyrenees and to which it is in some ways similar.
In Barcelona, there is a form of bilingualism which is probably unique. When
two people say goodbye, often one will say 'Adios' and the other will say
'Deu' or 'Adeu'. Everyone can understand both: Castilian, because it was the
only official language until Franco died in 1975; and Catalan, either
because it is their mother tongue, or because the regional government's law
to normalise the use of the language has been so successful.
The Generalitat's department of linguistics affirms that 94 per cent of the
population in Catalonia understands Catalan, though a large minority are
immigrants from other parts of Spain or the children of immigrants.
It even occasionally happens that a conversation between two friends is held
in both languages, with each speaking the language in which he is most
comfortable.
This pervasive bilingualism can occasionally be confusing for a visitor  -
for example, over street names. These are all signposted in Catalan, but are
often referred to in Castilian. There is not much difference between Passeig
de Gracia and Paseo de Gracia, but there is between Carrer Roger de Lluria
and Calle Lauria, or Carrer de l'Argenteria and Calle Plateria.
A director of the American Institute in Barcelona in the 1970s, shortly
after the restoration of democracy, is reputed not only to have learnt
Catalan but to have sung in the cors de Clav, traditional Catalan choirs.
This is about as far as it is possible to go, but it is at least wise to
know that Castilian is not the only official language.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
