<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 93 / FT Traveller, Barcelona (11): Market relatively buoyant
despite abundance of supply - Property / The number of projects currently
under way and falling rental prices are seen as good news by economic
promoters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUSTIN WEBSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE amount of office space in Barcelona has more than doubled since the
start of the Olympic building programme, and rental prices have tumbled from
a maximum of Pta 3,500 a square metre to between Pta 2,000 and Pta 2,500.
'It has been excellent,' said Manuel Ludevid, director of economic promotion
at the city council. 'If our companies do not go bankrupt - and the signs
are that they are not going bankrupt - we have a product which is twice as
good, better quality and cheaper.'
The market changed rapidly from one where there was a marked shortage of
supply to one where large buildings have been left empty, most notably the
MAFRE tower, one of the two skyscrapers in the Olympic village, owned by the
Spanish insurance company.
Also reaching completion is the huge L'Illa complex on Diagonal, which
includes 115,752 sq m of office space, and retail premises which have
already been taken by Marks and Spencer and Benetton, among others.
More than 20 major projects are currently under development, covering a
total of 1,000 hectares, according to the city council.
Lluis Armet, the deputy mayor, cites the proximity of all these projects to
the city centre as a reason for the relative buoyancy of the market under
such a weight of supply.
He also points to the involvement of insurance companies in several of the
developments - for example, Winterthur in the case of L'Illa - as a sign
that they attract 'investors who think in terms of long-term opportunities'.
As part of the first sector to be affected in the construction cycle, Josep
Maria Gordi, a Barcelona-based architect, has seen a steep drop in demand
for new building designs in the past two years. This has only recently begun
to show signs of recovering, but given the one constant factor - there is
still a shortage of land which can be built on - he does not expect prices
to fall much further.
</TEXT>
