<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 93 / FT Traveller, Barcelona (8): Philosopher speaks with the
voice of reason - Pasqual Maragall / Barcelona's mayor, a Mr Fixit in public
matters, is also a reflective scholar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHILE the public image of Pasqual Maragall is that of a can-do mayor, who
organised in his home town what are generally considered to be the best
Olympic games to date, the private persona is a deeply reflective
intellectual.
Mr Maragall is something of a philosopher mayor, who likes to discuss Sir
Ralf Dahrendorf, in the way that a philosopher king such as Frederick of
Prussia talked about Voltaire.
He toys with Sir Ralf's ideas about the 'centre of gravity' between civil
society and politics, between individual egoisms and general welfare.
Running a big city, which is what he has been doing for 11 years, since he
was 41, allows him plenty of scope to test and to formulate theories.
Mr Maragall may be a mayor, but he is also a scholar who studied at New
York's New School for Social Research and taught economics at Barcelona
University before he was drafted into city politics.
The city, says Barcelona's mayor, is where a proper gravity can be
established, where tensions can be overcome. He goes on to make bold claims:
'What Europe really has in its favour is a system of cities.' He asserts
that Europe's true roots, and therefore its best projection to the future,
lie 'not in the nations, not in the regions, but in the cities.'
In Mr Maragall's view, nations and regions rest on identity and are
exclusive - and that spells trouble. The cities are inclusive, and those who
live in them know that collective identity is not enough.
The urban nucleus, which is confined and complex, has historically ensured
'contacts' between its different components and established a 'system of
minimum guarantees'.
The upshot is that those who live in a Manchester, a Hamburg and a Barcelona
will always be able to 'understand each other', because the very stresses of
city life impose the 'minimums' and the 'contacts'. The same cannot be said,
Mr Maragall argues, 'for a Bosnia or a Flanders'.
The mayor believes Europe 'is going to be terrified of its diversity' and
that, because of this, the true value of cities will be realised. The cities
will become, if not exactly islands of mutual tolerance, at least 'safety
nets' where peaceful co-existence can be practised.
Mr Maragall dismisses the Hollywood vision of blade-runing urban wastelands
as a specifically 'American nightmare'. The city is not the enemy of the
human in Europe, and certainly not in Barcelona. In the philosopher mayor's
fiefdom, the gravitational pull is rational and reasonable.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
