<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 93 / FT Traveller, Barcelona (5): Plans put into action - The
Olympic Effect / Economic and strategic projects that were drawn up for the
year 2000 at the time of the Games remain the driving force behind continued
optimism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUSTIN WEBSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN in 1981 Barcelona city hall decided to enter the bidding to host the
Olympic Games, it was already looking for a way to realise its pent-up
ambitions.
Extensive urban plans dating back to 1978 for the regeneration of the city
were designed to correct the neglect it had suffered during the Franco
regime, when its suburbs grew and the centre became steadily more congested.
The success of its Olympic bid gave Barcelona a chance to make up that
deficit. 'In the five years before the Games,' said Lluis Armet, the deputy
mayor, 'public investment was the same as in the previous 30 or 40.'
Putting these plans into action not only took money, but also relied heavily
on the enthusiasm of the residents who had to live through the a period when
large parts of the city were turned into building sites, or obras, until it
became a popular joke that the city be renamed 'Bacelobra'.
The city hall made no secret of the fact that it saw the Games chiefly as a
means to an end. When earlier this year, it came to shouldering the deficit
of Holsa, the publicly-owned Olympic holding company, the central government
was not at first happy about forking out more cash.
According to Manuel Ludevid, head of economic promotion at the city hall,
this was partly because the hall had been responsible for its management and
because, he said, Madrid 'suspected, partly correctly, that some projects
which were not directly-related to the Games were passed through it'. It was
finally agreed that the deficit be shared.
What was directly-related to the Games was not easy to define. Only 9.4 per
cent of the recorded total figure of Pta 926,439m was spent on sports
facilities, for example; the rest on improvements in the transport system,
new hotels, telecommunications, the transformation of whole districts, such
as Vall d'Hebron and the Olympic Village, and the liberating of land for
building.
Spain's oldest railway, which ran along the coast and cut the city off from
the sea, was ripped up, for example, opening up the previously blighted area
for development, and prompting the overhaul of the city's inadequate
drainage system.
But not included in this total are all the other privately-funded projects
stimulated by this wave of urban renewal and upgrading of services. These
projects, such as the massive development of the coastal end of Diagonal,
the avenue which extends the whole way across the city, will at a slower
rate have as significant an impact as in the six years before the Games.
One legacy which the city has learnt to build on is the successful
co-operation between the private and public sectors. 'The Japanese example
is quite clear,' said Mr Ludevid, 'the Miti (ministry of trade and industry)
has been doing this for years, and it has had fantastic results.'
While the Olympic spirit of co-operation was still at full tilt, an economic
and strategic plan for the year 2000 was drawn up by 560 Catalan experts
from the government, the unions and business. This is one of the most
important factors behind the continued optimism, in spite of the harsh
economic climate.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
