<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 93 / FT Traveller, Barcelona (2): Axis for the twenty-first
century - Hub of the future / The city is gearing itself up to become a
gateway to southern Europe with a port to rival that of Rotterdam
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE expansion of Barcelona's airport is a measure of the confidence with
which the city faces its economic future. The airport tripled its total area
in the run up to the 1992 Olympic games and its four terminals now have the
capacity to handle 16m passengers a year - four times the population of
greater Barcelona and double the annual number of visitors that fly into the
city.
But the airport's under-capacity does not appear to worry anyone in
Barcelona. City hall officials, business leaders and academics share the
view that Barcelona is destined to become a 'Mediterranean Rotterdam', the
most important communications centre in southern Europe, the gateway to the
southern swathe of the Economic Community.
'We are talking about the motorways we have, the port we are building up and
the high-speed train we have been promised,' says Professor Joaquim Muns, a
senior member of the economics faculty at Barcelona University.
'The sum is a practical and efficient intermodal nucleus, a sort of
Rotterdam.'
Barcelona's economy, once rooted in its textile industry and latterly in car
and chemical manufacturing, is now increasingly viewed as being bound up in
its role as a gateway and a crossroads. Those who think Barcelona through
into the next century talk about the city's location and discuss the 'axis'
and the 'arc'.
The axis has to do with Spain and with its two high growth areas, the Ebro
river valley that meanders across north Spain to the Mediterranean and the
Mediterranean coast line itself. Barcelona stands at the motorway
intersection of these two expanding belts, well linked to Zaragoza, the Ebro
valley's focal point, and to the fast-growing Valencia nucleus that lies to
its south on the Mediterranean.
As, and when, Spain emerges from recession, wealth will again begin to flow
down the Ebro valley and up the Mediterranean coast to pass through
Barcelona on its way into northern Europe. It is no accident that the plants
of two of Spain's sturdiest, export-driven manufacturers - General Motors
and Ford - lie next to Zaragoza and Valencia respectively.
The arc relates to the Mediterranean stretch from northern Italy, through
southern France to north-eastern Spain which has some 50m inhabitants. This
area, which is coming to be known as the 'southern banana', is viewed as a
dynamic complement to the better known 'hot banana', the name given to the
central European arc that extends south from the Paris-London-Amsterdam
triangle along the Rhur valley to Milan and Lombardy.
Barcelona takes its local banana arc seriously for this is where the
Rotterdam analogy comes into play.
During the 1980s, the number of containers passing through the port of
Barcelona increased from 180,000 teu (twenty foot equivalent units) to
448,000. By 1991 the total was up to 488.917 teu, turning Barcelona into one
of the world's biggest Mediterranean ports and putting it comfortably ahead
of its closest competitors, Marseilles and Genoa.
The city projects itself as an intermodal distribution centre that will
quickly move maritime cargo arriving at its international container terminal
on to motorway and railways networks. With a view to consolidating
Barcelona's role as the centre of freight distribution for southern Europe,
the city's port authorities have a blueprint for a new container terminal
which will raise the harbour's handling capacity to 700,000 teu a year.
The future, as the city planners see it, has maritime cargoes from the
Pacific Rim saving four days in their journey to Europe by unloading at
Barcelona instead of at Rotterdam. Time saving will be greatly improved once
Barcelona is connected on a European-gauge track to Europe's high-speed
train network.
Freight traffic will make intensive use of the planned railway connection.
According to a forecast by Barcelona's city hall, 2.8m annual tonnes of
freight in the short term - the high speed network is scheduled to be
operating by 2004 - will rise to 4m tonnes in 2010. As a major European
entry point, Barcelona's vast airport might begin to fill up.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4491 Marine Cargo Handling.
</IN>
