<PROFILE>_AN-DKPCNAF8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>931116
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 93 / FT Traveller, Barcelona (1): Contrasts on every corner -
First impressions / Tom Burns finds that contradictions colour Barcelona
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHRISTOPHER COLUMBUS was the most famous traveller to reach Barcelona. The
statue that honours him at the harbour sums up the city's contradictory
nature.
On his return from his first voyage to the New World, Columbus went straight
to Barcelona where his patrons King Ferdinand and Queen Isabella had
temporarily established their travelling court.
But while Columbus - who presented the monarchs with slaves and parrots but
not much gold - announced that he had opened up the westward route to the
Indies, the harbour front statue to the discoverer has him looking in the
opposite direction, pointing east with his right arm towards his Italian
homeland.
Barcelona should probably not have a monument to Columbus at all. His
discovery shifted the whole direction of Spanish policy towards the Atlantic
and away from the Mediterranean. Barcelona itself was closed off from the
New World riches by the monopoly established in Seville.
Barcelona's contrasts are manifested in the emotional swings of its
inhabitants as they move between seny and rauxa. The Catalan word seny has
no Castilian Spanish equivalent and it means a mixture of business acumen
and commercial cunning. Rauxa, another wholly Catalan term, means boisterous
anarchy.
Barcelona has the most sober entrepreneurs in Spain but also the most zany
and outrageous experimental theatre. La Vanguardia, the city's
long-established quality newspaper, mixes excellent reporting and thoughtful
analysis with columns of luridly explicit small advertisements informing the
reader on who to 'contact', how to 'relax' and what can be roughly expected
in terms of cost and benefit.
The city's ability to be all things to all people extends to its political
institutions. Barcelona's municipal council is controlled by the socialist
party while the Catalan home rule government, which has its seat in the
city, is dominated by local nationalists whose ideological bent is decidedly
conservative.
The city hall and the Generalitat, the home rule government headquarters,
occupy opposite ends of the Sant Jaume square in the heart of old Barcelona
and eye each other suspiciously, the former from its the neo-classical
facade, the latter from its renaissance front. On important occasions, such
as the Olympics, politicians of both camps and institutions bury their
differences but at other times, petty squabbling is the norm.
Ever since elections started to be held again in Spain's post-Franco
democracy, Barcelona's residents have voted for the socialists in municipal
polls, for the nationalists in the local government ones and have had both
parties running neck and neck in general elections.
This entrenched dual track voting pattern could be an example of a
checks-and balances seny but it could just as easily be demonstration of the
rauxa syndrome that wants to keep everything confused.
The present day traveller to Barcelona will find contradictions on every
corner and in every restaurant. The local cuisine is adept at placing
opposites, such as lobster and chicken, in the same stew pot and
accompanying delicate fish grills with sauces - romescu and allioli - that
are calculated to blow the roof off a normal mouth.
From corner to corner, Barcelona architecturally embraces the modernist
fantasy of a Gaudi and the functionalism of a Mies van der Rohe, tight slums
that could be Naples and a grid street system punctured by solidly bourgeois
octagonal blocks with a Parisian feel to them.
The city's pace can be as fast as the traffic whizzing along its ring-roads
and as indolent as the crowds who amble along Las Ramblas.
Barcelona's contradictory character emerges in the tension between the
narrow Catalan provincialism that dominates so much of its city life and the
bravado of its European gateway claims. Its past has had it alternatively
squashed by Madrid and Castile, only to pick itself up again.
Typically, Catalonia's national day commemorates an 18th century defeat  -
one of the several occasions when its local privileges and national identity
were trampled on.
Now the city is riding triumphantly high. Astonishingly, after all the
building that went on before the Olympics, when the city was turned inside
out, building is still going on, although now it is mostly shopping
precincts that are going up rather than sports stadiums.
And yet there are doubts. The city council says it can cope with its massive
debts but the markets may need a certain amount of convincing. Huge inflows
of direct foreign investment appeared in the late 1980s but the likes of
Volkswagen and Nissan are having second thoughts.
Barcelona's see-saw history suggests that it will emerge from whatever
troubles lie ahead. Certainly its infrastructure is now magnificently
equipped to withstand a recession.
If not a single peseta was spent on the city for the rest of the century, it
would still look good in the year 2000.
The business visitor should take Barcelona's duality with an open mind.
There will be plenty of seny in the daytime and endless opportunity for
rauxa after hours.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
