<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow easier on bond yields,
Nafta worries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HAVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
RISING BOND yields and concern about the fate of the North American Free
Trade Agreement kept US share prices anchored in negative territory
yesterday, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 6.99 at 3,677.52. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost 1.64 at 463.75, while the American SE composite
shed 1.78 to 477.82 and the Nasdaq composite fell 6.87 to 772.45. New York
SE volume totalled 251m shares.
The markets opened the week in an uncertain mood. Although the economic
background continues to improve - official data yesterday showed that
industrial production rose a stronger than expected 0.8 per cent in October
 -investors remain troubled by several factors: rising bond yields, which
may be a precursor of higher short-term interest rates; the high valuations
of stock prices, which may lead to a substantial correction if investor
sentiment suddenly turns negative; and the possibility that congress may
reject Nafta tomorrow.
The worries about interest rates were at the forefront yesterday because of
an early rise in bond yields. The yield on the benchmark 30-year bond
initially climbed to 6.18 per cent in the wake of the strong industrial
production data, before falling back to the opening level. Nafta was also on
the minds of investors, who fear that if congress votes against Nafta this
week, long-term economic growth, and corporate profits, could suffer.
Shares of the major television network companies were all higher on news of
a court ruling that will allow networks to own financial stakes in shows
produced by outsiders. CBS jumped Dollars 8 1/4 to Dollars 303 1/8 and Cap
Cities ABC Dollars 11 5/8 to Dollars 630 3/4 , while General Electric,
parent of NBC, firmed Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 94 1/4 .
Paramount Communications fell Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 79 3/4 as investors
appeared unimpressed by a sweetened takeover offer from QVC Network. The
original agreed offer from Viacom still appears close to success in the bid
battle, although a court ruling today on the legality of a special
anti-takeover agreement between Paramount and Viacom may alter the final
outcome. Viacom shares were down Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 53 1/8 and QVC up
Dollars 2 1/8 at Dollars 51 3/4 .
Telefonos de Mexico, the biggest 'Nafta-play' in the market, fell Dollars 1
to Dollars 54 3/8 in volume of 4.6m shares on fears that the trade pact will
collapse.
UAL dropped Dollars 5 3/4 to Dollars 142 5/8 after broking house Bear
Stearns downgraded the airline's stock.
Canada
IN contrast to Mexico, Toronto stocks closed sharply lower as profit-taking
and worries over the outcome of tomorrow's Nafta vote in the US braked the
TSE's recent upward charge.
The TSE 300 index fell 21 points to 4,281.8 in trade of 76.8m shares valued
at CDollars 741m. Falls led rises by 475 to 331.
